# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transmission-lines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The **characteristic impedance** or **surge impedance** (usually written *Z*0) of a uniform transmission line is the ratio of the amplitudes of voltage and current of a wave travelling in one direction along the line in the absence of reflections in the other direction.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Equivalently, it can be defined as the input impedance of a transmission line when its length is infinite.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Characteristic impedance is determined by the geometry and materials of the transmission line and, for a uniform line, is not dependent on its length.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The SI unit of characteristic impedance is the ohm.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The characteristic impedance of a lossless transmission line is purely real, with no reactive component (see below).
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Energy supplied by a source at one end of such a line is transmitted through the line without being dissipated in the line itself.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] A transmission line of finite length (lossless or lossy) that is terminated at one end with an impedance equal to the characteristic impedance appears to the source like an infinitely long transmission line and produces no reflections.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The characteristic impedance *Z*(*ω*) of an infinite transmission line at a given angular frequency ω is the ratio of the voltage and current of a pure sinusoidal wave of the same frequency travelling along the line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This relation is also the case for finite transmission lines until the wave reaches the end of the line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Generally, a wave is reflected back along the line in the opposite direction.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] When the reflected wave reaches the source, it is reflected yet again, adding to the transmitted wave and changing the ratio of the voltage and current at the input, causing the voltage-current ratio to no longer equal the characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This new ratio including the reflected energy is called the input impedance of that particular transmission line and load.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The input impedance of an infinite line is equal to the characteristic impedance since the transmitted wave is never reflected back from the end.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Equivalently: *the characteristic impedance of a line is that impedance which, when terminating an arbitrary length of line at its output, produces an input impedance of equal value*.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This is so because there is no reflection on a line terminated in its own characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This expression extends to DC by letting ω tend to 0.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] A surge of energy on a finite transmission line will see an impedance of *Z*0 prior to any reflections returning; hence *surge impedance* is an alternative name for *characteristic impedance*.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Although an infinite line is assumed, since all quantities are per unit length, the “per length” parts of all the units cancel, and the characteristic impedance is independent of the length of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The voltage and current phasors on the line are related by the characteristic impedance as: $Z_{\text{0}}={\frac {V_{(+)}}{I_{(+)}}}=-{\frac {V_{(-)}}{I_{(-)}}}$ where the subscripts (+) and (−) mark the separate constants for the waves traveling forward (+) and backward (−).
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The rightmost expression has a negative sign because the current in the backward wave has the opposite direction to current in the forward wave.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] where the superscripts + and - represent forward- and backward-traveling waves, respectively.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The differential equations describing the dependence of the voltage and current on time and space are linear, so that a linear combination of solutions is again a solution.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This means that we can consider solutions with a time dependence $e^{j\omega t}$ .
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Doing so allows to factor out the time dependence, leaving an ordinary differential equation for the coefficients, which will be phasors, dependent on position (space) only.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Moreover, the parameters can be generalized to be frequency-dependent.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Consider a steady-state problem such that the voltage and current can be written as: ${\begin{aligned}v(x,t)&=V(x)e^{j\omega t}\\[.5ex]i(x,t)&=I(x)e^{j\omega t}\end{aligned}}$ Take the positive direction for V and I in the loop to be clockwise.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] It is called the **characteristic impedance** of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] For typical transmission lines, that are carefully built from wire with low loss resistance R and small insulation leakage conductance G; further, used for high frequencies, the inductive reactance ωL and the capacitive admittance ωC will both be large.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Consider an infinite ladder network consisting of a series impedance Z and a shunt admittance Y.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] If a new pair of impedance Z and admittance Y is added in front of the network, its input impedance *Z*IT remains unchanged since the network is infinite.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Thus, it can be reduced to a finite network with one series impedance Z and two parallel impedances 1/*Y* and *Z*IT.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Its input impedance is given by the expression $Z_{\mathrm {IT} }=Z+\left({\frac {\ 1\ }{Y}}\parallel Z_{\mathrm {IT} }\right)\$ which is also known as its iterative impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] For a transmission line, it can be seen as a limiting case of an infinite ladder network with infinitesimal impedance and admittance at a constant ratio.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Using this insight, many similar derivations exist in several books and are applicable to both lossless and lossy lines.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Here, we follow an approach posted by Tim Healy.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The line is modeled by a series of differential segments with differential series elements (*R* d*x*, *L* d*x*) and shunt elements (*C* d*x*, *G* d*x*) (as shown in the figure at the beginning of the article).
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The characteristic impedance is defined as the ratio of the input voltage to the input current of a semi-infinite length of line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] That is, the impedance looking into the line on the left is *Z*0.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] But, of course, if we go down the line one differential length d*x*, the impedance into the line is still *Z*0.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Hence we can say that the impedance looking into the line on the far left is equal to *Z*0 in parallel with *C* d*x* and *G* d*x*, all of which is in series with *R* d*x* and *L* d*x*.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The first-power d*x* terms are the highest remaining order.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] In comparison to the factors whose d*x* divided out, the last term, which still carries a remaining factor d*x*, is infinitesimal relative to the other, now finite terms, so we can drop it.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Reversing the sign ± applied to the square root has the effect of reversing the direction of the flow of current.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The analysis of lossless lines provides an accurate approximation for real transmission lines that simplifies the mathematics considered in modeling transmission lines.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] A lossless line is defined as a transmission line that has no line resistance and no dielectric loss.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] This would imply that the conductors act like perfect conductors and the dielectric acts like a perfect dielectric.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] In particular, *Z*0 does not depend any more upon the frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The above expression is wholly real, since the imaginary term j has canceled out, implying that *Z*0 is purely resistive.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] For a lossless line terminated in *Z*0, there is no loss of current across the line, and so the voltage remains the same along the line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The lossless line model is a useful approximation for many practical cases, such as low-loss transmission lines and transmission lines with high frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] For both of these cases, R and G are much smaller than *ωL* and *ωC*, respectively, and can thus be ignored.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Without a reflection of the wave, the load that is being supplied by the line effectively blends into the line making it appear to be an infinite line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] In a lossless line this implies that the voltage and current remain the same everywhere along the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Their magnitudes remain constant along the length of the line and are only rotated by a phase angle.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Loaded below its SIL, the voltage at the load will be greater than the system voltage.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Above it, the load voltage is depressed.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The Ferranti effect describes the voltage gain towards the remote end of a very lightly loaded (or open ended) transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Underground cables normally have a very low characteristic impedance, resulting in an SIL that is typically in excess of the thermal limit of the cable.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] The characteristic impedance of coaxial cables (coax) is commonly chosen to be 50 Ω for RF and microwave applications.
[src:transmission-lines/characteristic-impedance] Coax for video applications is usually 75 Ω for its lower loss .
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In electrical engineering, **impedance matching** is the practice of designing or adjusting the input impedance or output impedance of an electrical device for a desired value.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Often, the desired value is selected to maximize power transfer or minimize signal reflection.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For example, impedance matching typically is used to improve power transfer from a radio transmitter via the interconnecting transmission line to the antenna.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Signals on a transmission line will be transmitted without reflections if the transmission line is terminated with a matching impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Techniques of impedance matching include transformers, adjustable networks of lumped resistance, capacitance and inductance, or properly proportioned transmission lines.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Practical impedance-matching devices will generally provide best results over a specified frequency band.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The concept of impedance matching is widespread in electrical engineering, but is relevant in other applications in which a form of energy, not necessarily electrical, is transferred between a source and a load, such as in acoustics or optics.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Impedance characterizes the ratio of energy components in a given domain.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For constant signals, this impedance can also be constant.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For varying signals, it usually changes with frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The energy involved can be electrical, mechanical, acoustic, magnetic, electromagnetic, or thermal.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The concept of electrical impedance is perhaps the most commonly known.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Electrical impedance, like electrical resistance, is measured in ohms.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In general, impedance (symbol: *Z*) has a complex value; this means that loads generally have a resistance component (symbol: *R*) which forms the real part and a reactance component (symbol: *X*) which forms the imaginary part.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This impedance characterizes the ratio between the voltage and current components in the medium.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In simple cases (such as low-frequency or direct current power transmission) the reactance may be negligible or zero; the impedance can be considered a pure resistance, expressed as a real number.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In the following summary we will consider the general case when resistance and reactance are both significant, and the special case in which the reactance is negligible.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Complex conjugate matching is used when maximum power transfer is required, namely $Z_{\text{load}}=Z_{\text{source}}^{*},$ where a superscript * indicates the complex conjugate.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A conjugate match is different from a reflection-less match when either the source or load has a reactive component.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the source has a reactive component, but the load is purely resistive, then matching can be achieved by adding a reactance of the same magnitude but opposite sign to the load.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This simple matching network, consisting of a single element, will usually achieve a perfect match at only a single frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This is because the added element will either be a capacitor or an inductor, whose impedance in both cases is frequency dependent, and will not, in general, follow the frequency dependence of the source impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For wide bandwidth applications, a more complex network must be designed.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For two impedances to be complex conjugates their resistances must be equal, and their reactances must be equal in magnitude but of opposite signs.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In low-frequency or DC systems (or systems with purely resistive sources and loads) the reactances are zero, or small enough to be ignored.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In this case, maximum power transfer occurs when the resistance of the load is equal to the resistance of the source (see maximum power theorem for a mathematical proof).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Impedance matching is not always necessary.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For example, if delivering a high voltage (to reduce signal degradation or to reduce power consumption) is more important than maximizing power transfer, then *impedance bridging* or *voltage bridging* is often used.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In older audio systems (reliant on transformers and passive filter networks, and based on the telephone system), the source and load resistances were matched at 600 ohms.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] One reason for this was to maximize power transfer, as there were no amplifiers available that could restore lost signal.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Another reason was to ensure correct operation of the hybrid transformers used at central exchange equipment to separate outgoing from incoming speech, so these could be amplified or fed to a four-wire circuit.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Most modern audio circuits, on the other hand, use active amplification and filtering and can use voltage-bridging connections for greatest accuracy.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Strictly speaking, impedance matching only applies when both source and load devices are linear; however, matching may be obtained between nonlinear devices within certain operating ranges.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Adjusting the source impedance or the load impedance, in general, is called "impedance matching".
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] There are a variety of devices used between a source of energy and a load that perform "impedance matching".
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] To match electrical impedances, engineers use combinations of transformers, resistors, inductors, capacitors and transmission lines.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] These passive (and active) impedance-matching devices are optimized for different applications and include baluns, antenna tuners (sometimes called ATUs or roller-coasters, because of their appearance), acoustic horns, matching networks, and terminators.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Transformers are sometimes used to match the impedances of circuits.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A transformer converts alternating current at one voltage to the same waveform at another voltage.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The power input to the transformer and output from the transformer is the same (except for conversion losses).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The side with the lower voltage is at low impedance (because this has the lower number of turns), and the side with the higher voltage is at a higher impedance (as it has more turns in its coil).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] One example of this method involves a television balun transformer.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This transformer allows interfacing a balanced line (300-ohm twin-lead) and an unbalanced line (75-ohm coaxial cable such as RG-6).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] To match the impedances, both cables must be connected to a matching transformer with a turns ratio of 2:1.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In this example, the 300-ohm line is connected to the transformer side with more turns; the 75-ohm cable is connected to the transformer side with fewer turns.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Resistive impedance matches are easiest to design and can be achieved with a simple L pad consisting of two resistors.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Power loss is an unavoidable consequence of using resistive networks, and they are only (usually) used to transfer line level signals.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Most lumped-element devices can match a specific range of load impedances.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For example, in order to match an inductive load into a real impedance, a capacitor needs to be used.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the load impedance becomes capacitive, the matching element must be replaced by an inductor.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In many cases, there is a need to use the same circuit to match a broad range of load impedance and thus simplify the circuit design.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This issue was addressed by the stepped transmission line, where multiple, serially placed, quarter-wave dielectric slugs are used to vary a transmission line's characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] By controlling the position of each element, a broad range of load impedances can be matched without having to reconnect the circuit.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Filters are frequently used to achieve impedance matching in telecommunications and radio engineering.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In general, it is not theoretically possible to achieve perfect impedance matching at all frequencies with a network of discrete components.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Impedance matching networks are designed with a definite bandwidth, take the form of a filter, and use filter theory in their design.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Applications requiring only a narrow bandwidth, such as radio tuners and transmitters, might use a simple tuned filter such as a stub.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This would provide a perfect match at one specific frequency only.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Wide bandwidth matching requires filters with multiple sections.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A simple electrical impedance-matching network requires one capacitor and one inductor.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In the figure to the right, R1 > R2, however, either R1 or R2 may be the source and the other the load.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] One of X1 or X2 must be an inductor and the other must be a capacitor.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] One reactance is in parallel with the source (or load), and the other is in series with the load (or source).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If a reactance is in parallel *with the source*, the effective network matches from high to low impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Consider a real source impedance of $R_{1}$ and real load impedance of $R_{2}$ .
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Note, $X_{1}$ , the reactance in parallel, has a negative reactance because it is typically a capacitor.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This gives the L-network the additional feature of harmonic suppression since it is a low pass filter too.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The inverse connection (impedance step-up) is simply the reverse—for example, reactance in series with the source.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The magnitude of the impedance ratio is limited by reactance losses such as the Q of the inductor.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Multiple L-sections can be wired in cascade to achieve higher impedance ratios or greater bandwidth.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Transmission line matching networks can be modeled as infinitely many L-sections wired in cascade.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Optimal matching circuits can be designed for a particular system using Smith charts.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Power factor correction devices are intended to cancel the reactive and nonlinear characteristics of a load at the end of a power line.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This causes the load seen by the power line to be purely resistive.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For a given true power required by a load this minimizes the true current supplied through the power lines, and minimizes power wasted in the resistance of those power lines.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For example, a maximum power point tracker is used to extract the maximum power from a solar panel and efficiently transfer it to batteries, the power grid or other loads.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The maximum power theorem applies to its "upstream" connection to the solar panel, so it emulates a load resistance equal to the solar panel source resistance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] However, the maximum power theorem does not apply to its "downstream" connection.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] That connection is an impedance bridging connection; it emulates a high-voltage, low-resistance source to maximize efficiency.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] On the power grid the overall load is usually inductive.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Consequently, power factor correction is most commonly achieved with banks of capacitors.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] It is only necessary for correction to be achieved at one single frequency, the frequency of the supply.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Complex networks are only required when a band of frequencies must be matched and this is the reason why simple capacitors are all that is usually required for power factor correction.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In RF connections, impedance matching is desirable, because otherwise reflections may be created at the end of the mismatched transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The reflection may cause frequency-dependent loss.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In radio-frequency (RF) systems, a common value for source and load impedances is 50 ohms.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A typical RF load is a quarter-wave ground plane antenna (37 ohms with an ideal ground plane).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] so the reflection coefficient is the same (except for sign), no matter from which direction the wave approaches the boundary.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] There is also a current reflection coefficient, which is the negative of the voltage reflection coefficient.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the wave encounters an open at the load end, positive voltage and negative current pulses are transmitted back toward the source (negative current means the current is going the opposite direction).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Thus, at each boundary there are four reflection coefficients (voltage and current on one side, and voltage and current on the other side).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] All four are the same, except that two are positive and two are negative.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The voltage reflection coefficient and current reflection coefficient on the same side have opposite signs.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Voltage reflection coefficients on opposite sides of the boundary have opposite signs.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Because they are all the same except for sign it is traditional to interpret the reflection coefficient as the voltage reflection coefficient (unless otherwise indicated).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Either end (or both ends) of a transmission line can be a source or a load (or both), so there is no inherent preference for which side of the boundary is medium 1 and which side is medium 2.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] With a single transmission line it is customary to define the voltage reflection coefficient for a wave incident on the boundary from the transmission line side, regardless of whether a source or load is connected on the other side.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In a transmission line, a wave travels from the source along the line.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Suppose the wave hits a boundary (an abrupt change in impedance).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Some of the wave is reflected back, while some keeps moving onwards.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is incident on the boundary from the source side.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is transmitted to the load.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is reflected back toward the source.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] where $\Gamma _{TL}\,$ is the reflection coefficient going from the transmission line to the load.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The source of waves incident from the line are the reflections from the load end.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the source impedance matches the line, reflections from the load end will be absorbed at the source end.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the transmission line is not matched at both ends reflections from the load will be re-reflected at the source and re-re-reflected at the load end *ad infinitum*, losing energy on each transit of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This can cause a resonance condition and strongly frequency-dependent behavior.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In a narrow-band system this can be desirable for matching, but is generally undesirable in a wide-band system.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] where $T\ ,$ is the one-way transfer function (from either end to the other) when the transmission line is exactly matched at source and load. $T\,$ accounts for everything that happens to the signal in transit (including delay, attenuation and dispersion).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] where $V_{S}\,$ is the open circuit (or unloaded) output voltage from the source.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Telephone systems also use matched impedances to minimise echo on long-distance lines.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This is related to transmission-line theory.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Matching also enables the telephone *hybrid coil* (2- to 4-wire conversion) to operate correctly.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] As the signals are sent and received on the same two-wire circuit to the central office (or exchange), cancellation is necessary at the telephone earpiece so excessive sidetone is not heard.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] All devices used in telephone signal paths are generally dependent on matched cable, source and load impedances.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In the local loop, the impedance chosen is 600 ohms (nominal).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Terminating networks are installed at the exchange to offer the best match to their subscriber lines.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Each country has its own standard for these networks, but they are all designed to approximate about 600 ohms over the voice frequency band.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Audio amplifiers typically do not match impedances, but provide an output impedance that is lower than the load impedance (such as < 0.1 ohm in typical semiconductor amplifiers), for improved speaker damping.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For vacuum tube amplifiers, impedance-changing transformers are often used to get a low output impedance, and to better match the amplifier's performance to the load impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Some tube amplifiers have output transformer taps to adapt the amplifier output to typical loudspeaker impedances.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The impedance of the loudspeaker on the secondary coil of the transformer will be transformed to a higher impedance on the primary coil in the circuit of the power pentodes by the square of the turns ratio, which forms the *impedance scaling factor*.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The output stage in common-drain or common-collector semiconductor-based end stages with MOSFETs or power transistors has a very low output impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If they are properly balanced, there is no need for a transformer or a large electrolytic capacitor to separate AC from DC current.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In NMR techniques (NMR spectroscopy and MR imaging), impedance matching is required to adjust power transfer to the radiofrequency antenna depending on the sample present in the system.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] It is typically performed automatically (in clinical imaging systems for instance) or manually, before acquisitions take place.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The radiofrequency antennas are equipped with variable "match" and "tune" adjusting screws which enable the user or the system to adjust the center frequency and the level of power transfer at the same time.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Similar to electrical transmission lines, an impedance matching problem exists when transferring sound energy from one medium to another.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the acoustic impedance of the two media are very different most sound energy will be reflected (or absorbed), rather than transferred across the border.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The gel used in medical ultrasonography helps transfer acoustic energy from the transducer to the body and back again.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Without the gel, the impedance mismatch in the transducer-to-air and the air-to-body discontinuity reflects almost all the energy, leaving very little to go into the body.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The bones in the middle ear function as a series of levers, which matches mechanical impedance between the eardrum (which is acted upon by vibrations in air) and the fluid-filled inner ear.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Horns in loudspeaker systems are used like transformers in electrical circuits to match the impedance of the transducer to the impedance of the air.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This principle is used in both horn loudspeakers and musical instruments.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Because most driver impedances are poorly matched to the impedance of free air at low frequencies, loudspeaker enclosures are designed to both match impedance and minimize destructive phase cancellations between output from the front and rear of a speaker cone.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The loudness of sound produced in air from a loudspeaker is directly related to the ratio of the diameter of the speaker to the wavelength of the sound being produced: larger speakers can produce lower frequencies at a higher level than smaller speakers.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Elliptical speakers are a complex case, acting like large speakers lengthwise and small speakers crosswise.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Acoustic impedance matching (or the lack of it) affects the operation of a megaphone, an echo and soundproofing.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A similar effect occurs when light (or any electromagnetic wave) hits the interface between two media with different refractive indices.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic materials, the refractive index is inversely proportional to the material's characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] to calculate reflection and transmission coefficients for the interface.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic dielectrics, this equation is equivalent to the Fresnel equations.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Unwanted reflections can be reduced by the use of an anti-reflection optical coating.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If a body of mass *m* collides elastically with a second body, maximum energy transfer to the second body will occur when the second body has the same mass *m*.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In a head-on collision of equal masses, the energy of the first body will be completely transferred to the second body (as in Newton's cradle for example).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] In this case, the masses act as "mechanical impedances", which must be matched to maximize energy transfer.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] which is analogous to the power-transfer equation.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If we cannot change the masses of bodies, then we can match their impedance with a lever.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] Imagine a large ball dropping to the ground, and a small ball lying on the ground.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The large ball hits the short end of a lever, and the small ball is launched from the long end of the lever.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If the lever arm lengths satisfy $l_{1}m_{1}=l_{2}m_{2}$ , then all energy would be transferred to the small ball if collisions are elastic.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] This is roughly how the middle ear works (see above).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] These principles are useful in the application of highly energetic materials (explosives).
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] If an explosive charge is placed on a target, the sudden release of energy causes compression waves to propagate through the target radially from the point-charge contact.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] When the compression waves reach areas of high acoustic impedance mismatch (such as the opposite side of the target), tension waves reflect back and create spalling.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] The greater the mismatch, the greater the effect of creasing and spalling will be.
[src:transmission-lines/impedance-matching] A charge initiated against a wall with air behind it will do more damage to the wall than a charge initiated against a wall with soil behind it.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In physics and electrical engineering the **reflection coefficient** is a parameter that describes how much of a wave is reflected by an impedance discontinuity in the transmission medium.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] It is equal to the ratio of the amplitude of the reflected wave to the incident wave, with each expressed as phasors.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] For example, it is used in optics to calculate the amount of light that is reflected from a surface with a different index of refraction, such as a glass surface, or in an electrical transmission line to calculate how much of the electromagnetic wave is reflected by an impedance discontinuity.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient is closely related to the *transmission coefficient*.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflectance of a system is also sometimes called a reflection coefficient.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Different disciplines have different applications for the term.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In telecommunications and transmission line theory, the reflection coefficient is the ratio of the complex amplitude of the reflected wave to that of the incident wave.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The voltage and current at any point along a transmission line can always be resolved into forward and reflected traveling waves given a specified reference impedance *Z0*.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reference impedance used is typically the characteristic impedance of a transmission line that's involved, but one can speak of reflection coefficient without any actual transmission line being present.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In terms of the forward and reflected waves determined by the voltage and current, the reflection coefficient is defined as the complex ratio of the voltage of the reflected wave ( $V^{-}$ ) to that of the incident wave ( $V^{+}$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient may also be established using other field or circuit pairs of quantities whose product defines power resolvable into a forward and reverse wave.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In the accompanying figure, a signal source with internal impedance $Z_{S}$ possibly followed by a transmission line of characteristic impedance $Z_{S}$ is represented by its Thévenin equivalent, driving the load $Z_{L}$ .
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] For a real (resistive) source impedance $Z_{S}$ , if we define $\Gamma$ using the reference impedance $Z_{0}=Z_{S}$ then the source's maximum power is delivered to a load $Z_{L}=Z_{0}$ , in which case $\Gamma =0$ implying no reflected power.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] More generally, the squared-magnitude of the reflection coefficient $|\Gamma |^{2}$ denotes the proportion of that power that is reflected back to the source, with the power actually delivered toward the load being $1-|\Gamma |^{2}$ .
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Anywhere along an intervening (lossless) transmission line of characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ , the magnitude of the reflection coefficient $|\Gamma |$ will remain the same (the powers of the forward and reflected waves stay the same) but with a different phase.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In the case of a short circuited load ( $Z_{L}=0$ ), one finds $\Gamma =-1$ at the load.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] This implies the reflected wave having a 180° phase shift (phase reversal) with the voltages of the two waves being opposite at that point and adding to zero (as a short circuit demands).
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient is determined by the load impedance at the end of the transmission line, as well as the characteristic impedance of the line.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient can also be measured at other points on the line.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The *magnitude* of the reflection coefficient in a lossless transmission line is constant along the line (as are the powers in the forward and reflected waves).
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] However its *phase* will be shifted by an amount dependent on the electrical distance $\phi$ from the load.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Note that the phase of the reflection coefficient is changed by *twice* the phase length of the attached transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] That is to take into account not only the phase delay of the reflected wave, but the phase shift that had first been applied to the forward wave, with the reflection coefficient being the quotient of these.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient so measured, $\Gamma '$ , corresponds to an impedance which is generally dissimilar to $Z_{L}$ present at the far side of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The complex reflection coefficient (in the region $|\Gamma |\leq 1$ , corresponding to passive loads) may be displayed graphically using a Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The Smith chart is a polar plot of $\Gamma$ , therefore the magnitude of $\Gamma$ is given directly by the distance of a point to the center (with the edge of the Smith chart corresponding to $|\Gamma |=1$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Its evolution along a transmission line is likewise described by a rotation of $2\phi$ around the chart's center.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Using the scales on a Smith chart, the resulting impedance (normalized to $Z_{0}$ ) can directly be read.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Before the advent of modern electronic computers, the Smith chart was of particular use as a sort of analog computer for this purpose.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Along a lossless transmission line of characteristic impedance *Z*0, the SWR signifies the ratio of the voltage (or current) maxima to minima (or what it would be if the transmission line were long enough to produce them).
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The above calculation assumes that $\Gamma$ has been calculated using *Z*0 as the reference impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Since it uses only the *magnitude* of $\Gamma$ , the SWR intentionally ignores the specific value of the load impedance *ZL* responsible for it, but only the magnitude of the resulting impedance mismatch.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] That SWR remains the same wherever measured along a transmission line (looking towards the load) since the addition of a transmission line length to a load $Z_{L}$ only changes the phase, not magnitude of $\Gamma$ .
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] While having a one-to-one correspondence with reflection coefficient, SWR is the most commonly used figure of merit in describing the mismatch affecting a radio antenna or antenna system.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] It is most often measured at the transmitter side of a transmission line, but having, as explained, the same value as would be measured at the antenna (load) itself.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] A transmission line is an example of a 2-port electrical network, but reflection coefficients are useful in the analysis of any electrical networks.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] A reflection coefficient for each port in the same way as for the boundary of a transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] It will, however, also depend on the properties of connections at other ports and so is not a property intrinsic to the network itself.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Reflection coefficient is used in feeder testing for reliability of medium.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] In optics and electromagnetics in general, *reflection coefficient* can refer to either the amplitude reflection coefficient described here, or the reflectance, depending on context.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Typically, the reflectance is represented by a capital *R*, while the amplitude reflection coefficient is represented by a lower-case *r*.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] These related concepts are covered by Fresnel equations in classical optics.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] Acousticians use reflection coefficients to understand the effect of different materials on their acoustic environments.
[src:transmission-lines/reflection-coefficient] The field properties used to define the reflection coefficient are typically the acoustic pressure and velocity in the incident and reflected acoustic waves.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] space (where the lines appear as circles).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] It was independently proposed by Tōsaku Mizuhashi (水橋東作) in 1937, and by Amiel R.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Volpert (Амиэ́ль Р. Во́льперт) and Phillip H.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Starting with a rectangular diagram, Smith had developed a special polar coordinate chart by 1936, which, with the input of his colleagues Enoch B.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] McRae, who were familiar with conformal mappings, was reworked into the final form in early 1937, which was eventually published in January 1939.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart can be used to simultaneously display multiple parameters including impedances, admittances, reflection coefficients, $S_{nn}\,$ scattering parameters, noise figure circles, constant gain contours and regions for unconditional stability.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is most frequently used at or within the unity radius region.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] However, the remainder is still mathematically relevant, being used, for example, in oscillator design and stability analysis.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Thus most RF circuit analysis software includes a Smith chart option for the display of results and all but the simplest impedance measuring instruments can plot measured results on a Smith chart display.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is a mathematical transformation of the two-dimensional Cartesian complex plane.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Complex numbers with positive real parts map inside the circle.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Those with negative real parts map outside the circle.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If we are dealing only with impedances with non-negative resistive components, our interest is focused on the area inside the circle.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] where *z* = ⁠*Z*/*Z*0⁠, i.e., the complex impedance, Z, normalized by the reference impedance, *Z*0.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The impedance Smith chart is then an Argand plot of impedances thus transformed.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Impedances with non-negative resistive components will appear inside a circle with unit radius; the origin will correspond to the reference impedance, *Z*0.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is plotted on the complex reflection coefficient plane in two dimensions and may be scaled in normalised impedance (the most common), normalised admittance or both, using different colours to distinguish between them.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] These are often known as the Z, Y and YZ Smith charts respectively.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Normalised scaling allows the Smith chart to be used for problems involving any characteristic or system impedance which is represented by the center point of the chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The most commonly used normalization impedance is 50 ohms.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Once an answer is obtained through the graphical constructions described below, it is straightforward to convert between normalised impedance (or normalised admittance) and the corresponding unnormalized value by multiplying by the characteristic impedance (admittance).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Reflection coefficients can be read directly from the chart as they are unitless parameters.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart has a scale around its circumference or periphery which is graduated in wavelengths and degrees.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The wavelengths scale is used in distributed component problems and represents the distance measured along the transmission line connected between the generator or source and the load to the point under consideration.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The degrees scale represents the angle of the voltage reflection coefficient at that point.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart may also be used for lumped-element matching and analysis problems.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Use of the Smith chart and the interpretation of the results obtained using it requires a good understanding of AC circuit theory and transmission-line theory, both of which are prerequisites for RF engineers.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] As impedances and admittances change with frequency, problems using the Smith chart can only be solved manually using one frequency at a time, the result being represented by a point.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This is often adequate for narrow band applications (typically up to about 5% to 10% bandwidth) but for wider bandwidths it is usually necessary to apply Smith chart techniques at more than one frequency across the operating frequency band.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Provided the frequencies are sufficiently close, the resulting Smith chart points may be joined by straight lines to create a locus.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The accuracy of the Smith chart is reduced for problems involving a large locus of impedances or admittances, although the scaling can be magnified for individual areas to accommodate these.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The SI unit of impedance is the ohm with the symbol of the upper case Greek letter omega (Ω) and the SI unit for admittance is the siemens with the symbol of an upper case letter S.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Normalised impedance and normalised admittance are dimensionless.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Actual impedances and admittances must be normalised before using them on a Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Once the result is obtained it may be de-normalised to obtain the actual result.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is used with one frequency ( $\omega$ ) at a time, and only for one moment ( t ) at a time, so the temporal part of the phase ( $\exp(j\omega t)\,$ ) is fixed.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] All terms are actually multiplied by this to obtain the instantaneous phase, but it is conventional and understood to omit it.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] where $A\,$ and $B\,$ are respectively the forward and reverse voltage amplitudes at the load.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The complex voltage reflection coefficient $\Gamma \,$ is defined as the ratio of the reflected wave to the incident (or forward) wave.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For a uniform transmission line (in which $\gamma \,$ is constant), the complex reflection coefficient of a standing wave varies according to the position on the line.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If the line is lossy ( $\alpha \,$ is non-zero) this is represented on the Smith chart by a spiral path.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In most Smith chart problems however, losses can be assumed negligible ( $\alpha \approx 0\,$ ) and the task of solving them is greatly simplified.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] where $\Gamma _{\text{L}}\,$ is the reflection coefficient at the load, and $\ell \,$ is the line length from the load to the location where the reflection coefficient is measured.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] where $\lambda \,$ is the wavelength *within the transmission line* at the test frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This equation shows that, for a standing wave, the complex reflection coefficient and impedance repeats every half wavelength along the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The complex reflection coefficient is generally simply referred to as reflection coefficient.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The outer circumferential scale of the Smith chart represents the distance from the generator to the load scaled in wavelengths and is therefore scaled from zero to 0.50.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] These are the equations which are used to construct the Z Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Mathematically speaking $\,\Gamma \,$ and $\,z_{\mathsf {T}}\,$ are related via a Möbius transformation.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Both $\,\Gamma \,$ and $\,z_{\mathsf {T}}\,$ are expressed in complex numbers without any units.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] They both change with frequency so for any particular measurement, the frequency at which it was performed must be stated together with the characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] $\,\Gamma \,$ may be expressed in magnitude and angle on a polar diagram.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Any actual reflection coefficient must have a magnitude of less than or equal to unity so, at the test frequency, this may be expressed by a point inside a circle of unity radius.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is actually constructed on such a polar diagram.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart scaling is designed in such a way that reflection coefficient can be converted to normalised impedance or vice versa.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Using the Smith chart, the normalised impedance may be obtained with appreciable accuracy by plotting the point representing the reflection coefficient *treating the Smith chart as a polar diagram* and then reading its value directly using the characteristic Smith chart scaling.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This technique is a graphical alternative to substituting the values in the equations.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Versions of the transmission-line equation may be similarly derived for the admittance loss free case and for the impedance and admittance lossy cases.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart graphical equivalent of using the transmission-line equation is to normalise $\,Z_{\mathsf {L}}\,,$ to plot the resulting point on a Z Smith chart and to draw a circle through that point centred at the Smith chart centre.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The path along the arc of the circle represents how the impedance changes whilst moving along the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In this case the circumferential (wavelength) scaling must be used, remembering that this is the wavelength within the transmission line and may differ from the free space wavelength.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If a polar diagram is mapped on to a cartesian coordinate system it is conventional to measure angles relative to the positive x-axis using a counterclockwise direction for positive angles.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The magnitude of a complex number is the length of a straight line drawn from the origin to the point representing it.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If the termination is perfectly matched, the reflection coefficient will be zero, represented effectively by a circle of zero radius or in fact a point at the centre of the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If the termination was a perfect open circuit or short circuit the magnitude of the reflection coefficient would be unity, all power would be reflected and the point would lie at some point on the unity circumference circle.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart is composed of two families of circles: circles of constant normalised resistance (constant lines of $\Re e[z]$ ) and circles of constant normalised reactance (constant lines of $\Im m[z]$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In the complex reflection coefficient plane the Smith chart occupies a circle of unity radius centred at the origin.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In cartesian coordinates therefore the circle would pass through the points (+1,0) and (−1,0) on the x-axis and the points (0,+1) and (0,−1) on the y-axis.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This equation produces circles when plotting lines of constant $\Re e[z]$ or constant $\Im m[z]$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For passive pasive components, the lines of the Smith charted are only plotted for values of $\Re e[z]>0$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] A point with a reflection coefficient magnitude 0.63 and angle 60° represented in polar form as $0.63\angle 60^{\circ }\,$ , is shown as point P1 on the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] To plot this, one may use the circumferential (reflection coefficient) angle scale to find the $\angle 60^{\circ }\,$ graduation and a ruler to draw a line passing through this and the centre of the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The length of the line would then be scaled to P1 assuming the Smith chart radius to be unity.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For example, if the actual radius measured from the paper was 100 mm, the length OP1 would be 63 mm.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The following table gives some similar examples of points which are plotted on the *Z* Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For each, the reflection coefficient is given in polar form together with the corresponding normalised impedance in rectangular form.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The conversion may be read directly from the Smith chart or by substitution into the equation.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In RF circuit and matching problems sometimes it is more convenient to work with admittances (representing conductances and susceptances) and sometimes it is more convenient to work with impedances (representing resistances and reactances).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Solving a typical matching problem will often require several changes between both types of Smith chart, using normalised impedance for series elements and normalised admittances for parallel elements.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For these a dual (normalised) impedance and admittance Smith chart may be used.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Alternatively, one type may be used and the scaling converted to the other when required.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In order to change from normalised impedance to normalised admittance or vice versa, the point representing the value of reflection coefficient under consideration is moved through exactly 180 degrees at the same radius.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For example, the point P1 in the example representing a reflection coefficient of $0.63\angle 60^{\circ }\,$ has a normalised impedance of $z_{P}=0.80+j1.40\,$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] To graphically change this to the equivalent normalised admittance point, say Q1, a line is drawn with a ruler from P1 through the Smith chart centre to Q1, an equal radius in the opposite direction.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This is equivalent to moving the point through a circular path of exactly 180 degrees.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Reading the value from the Smith chart for Q1, remembering that the scaling is now in normalised admittance, gives $y_{P}=0.30-j0.54\,$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Once a transformation from impedance to admittance has been performed, the scaling changes to normalised admittance until a later transformation back to normalised impedance is performed.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The table below shows examples of normalised impedances and their equivalent normalised admittances obtained by rotation of the point through 180°.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Again, these may be obtained either by calculation or using a Smith chart as shown, converting between the normalised impedance and normalised admittances planes.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The choice of whether to use the *Z* Smith chart or the *Y* Smith chart for any particular calculation depends on which is more convenient.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Impedances in series and admittances in parallel add while impedances in parallel and admittances in series are related by a reciprocal equation.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Dealing with the reciprocals, especially in complex numbers, is more time-consuming and error-prone than using linear addition.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In general therefore, most RF engineers work in the plane where the circuit topography supports linear addition.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The following table gives the complex expressions for impedance (real and normalised) and admittance (real and normalised) for each of the three basic passive circuit elements: resistance, inductance and capacitance.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Using just the characteristic impedance (or characteristic admittance) and test frequency an equivalent circuit can be found and vice versa.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Distributed matching becomes feasible and is sometimes required when the physical size of the matching components is more than about 5% of a wavelength at the operating frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Here the electrical behaviour of many lumped components becomes rather unpredictable.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This occurs in microwave circuits and when high power requires large components in shortwave, FM and TV broadcasting.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] For distributed components the effects on reflection coefficient and impedance of moving along the transmission line must be allowed for using the outer circumferential scale of the Smith chart which is calibrated in wavelengths.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The following example shows how a transmission line, terminated with an arbitrary load, may be matched at one frequency either with a series or parallel reactive component in each case connected at precise positions.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Supposing a loss-free air-spaced transmission line of characteristic impedance $Z_{0}=50\ \Omega$ , operating at a frequency of 800 MHz, is terminated with a circuit comprising a 17.5 $\Omega$ resistor in series with a 6.5 nanohenry (6.5 nH) inductor.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This is plotted on the Z Smith chart at point P20.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The line OP20 is extended through to the wavelength scale where it intersects at the point $L_{1}=0.098\lambda \,$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] As the transmission line is loss free, a circle centred at the centre of the Smith chart is drawn through the point P20 to represent the path of the constant magnitude reflection coefficient due to the termination.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] where $c\,$ is the velocity of electromagnetic radiation in free space and $f\,$ is the frequency in hertz.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The result gives $\lambda =375\ \mathrm {mm} \,$ , making the position of the matching component 29.6 mm from the load.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] To match the termination at 800 MHz, a series capacitor of 2.6 pF must be placed in series with the transmission line at a distance of 29.6 mm from the termination.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] An alternative shunt match could be calculated after performing a Smith chart transformation from normalised impedance to normalised admittance.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Point Q20 is the equivalent of P20 but expressed as a normalised admittance.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] (In fact this value is not actually used).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] However, the extension of the line OQ20 through to the wavelength scale gives $L_{3}=0.152\lambda \,$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] From the table it can be seen that a negative admittance would require an inductor, connected in parallel with the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] A suitable inductive shunt matching would therefore be a 6.5 nH inductor in parallel with the line positioned at 123 mm from the load.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The analysis of lumped-element components assumes that the wavelength at the frequency of operation is much greater than the dimensions of the components themselves.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart may be used to analyze such circuits in which case the movements around the chart are generated by the (normalized) impedances and admittances of the components at the frequency of operation.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In this case the wavelength scaling on the Smith chart circumference is not used.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The following circuit will be analyzed using a Smith chart at an operating frequency of 100 MHz.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] At this frequency the free space wavelength is 3 m.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The component dimensions themselves will be in the order of millimetres so the assumption of lumped components will be valid.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Despite there being no transmission line as such, a system impedance must still be defined to enable normalization and de-normalization calculations and $Z_{0}=50\ \Omega \,$ is a good choice here as $R_{1}=50\ \Omega \,$ .
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If there were very different values of resistance present a value closer to these might be a better choice.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The analysis starts with a Z Smith chart looking into R1 only with no other components present.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] As $R_{1}=50\ \Omega \,$ is the same as the system impedance, this is represented by a point at the centre of the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The first transformation is OP1 along the line of constant normalized resistance in this case the addition of a normalized reactance of -*j*0.80, corresponding to a series capacitor of 40 pF.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Points with suffix P are in the *Z* plane and points with suffix Q are in the *Y* plane.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Therefore, transformations *P*1 to *Q*1 and *P*3 to *Q*3 are from the Z Smith chart to the Y Smith chart and transformation *Q*2 to *P*2 is from the Y Smith chart to the Z Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The following table shows the steps taken to work through the remaining components and transformations, returning eventually back to the centre of the Smith chart and a perfect 50 ohm match.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Y Smith chart is constructed in a similar way to the Z Smith chart case but by expressing values of voltage reflection coefficient in terms of normalised admittance instead of normalised impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Y Smith chart appears like the normalised impedance, type but with the graphic nested circles rotated through 180°, but the numeric scale remaining in its same position (not rotated) as the Z chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The region above the x-axis represents capacitive admittances and the region below the x-axis represents inductive admittances.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Capacitive admittances have positive imaginary parts and inductive admittances have negative imaginary parts.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] Again, if the termination is perfectly matched the reflection coefficient will be zero, represented by a 'circle' of zero radius or in fact a point at the centre of the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] If the termination was a perfect open or short circuit the magnitude of the voltage reflection coefficient would be unity, all power would be reflected and the point would lie at some point on the unity circumference circle of the Smith chart.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The Smith chart can be extended for negative resistance $(\Re e[z]<0)$ , but such an extended chart is rarely used in practice.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In such cases, the amplitude of the reflection coeffient, $\Gamma$ , is greater than 1, which means more energy is reflected than was incident.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This is not necessarily a violation of the concept of the conservation of energy, as it is the usual case of electronic amplification in which the additional power is taken from an external DC bias.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In 2011, Muller, *et al* proposed a mapping of the Smith chart from the two-dimension complex plane for the reflection coefficient, $\Gamma$ , into a Riemann sphere.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The mapping from the plane to the sphere is accomplished using a stereographic projection.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The last two characteristics mean that the infinite plane of the exterior of the circle $\Gamma =1$ maps on to a finite hemisphere.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] This is why all the circles contain that point.
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] In 2020, Muller, *et al* offered a new use for the Smith chart on a sphere in which they plotted parameters such as group delays and Q factors outside the sphere (rather than on the sphere).
[src:transmission-lines/smith-chart] The visual frequency orientation (clockwise vs. counter-clockwise) enables one to differentiate between a negative / capacitance and positive / inductive whose reflection coefficients are the same when plotted on a 2D Smith chart, but whose orientations diverge as frequency increases.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In radio engineering and telecommunications, **standing wave ratio** (**SWR**) is a measure of impedance matching of loads to the characteristic impedance of a transmission line or waveguide.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Impedance mismatches result in standing waves along the transmission line, and SWR is defined as the ratio of the partial standing wave's amplitude at an antinode (maximum) to the amplitude at a node (minimum) along the line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] A SWR can be also defined as the ratio of the maximum amplitude to minimum amplitude of the transmission line's currents, electric field strength, or the magnetic field strength.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Neglecting transmission line loss, these ratios are identical.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The **power standing wave ratio** (**PSWR**) is defined as the square of the VSWR, however, this deprecated term has no direct physical relation to power actually involved in transmission.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] SWR is usually measured using a dedicated instrument called an SWR meter.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In practice most transmission lines used in these applications are coaxial cables with an impedance of either 50 or 75 ohms, so most SWR meters correspond to one of these.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Checking the SWR is a standard procedure in a radio station.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Although the same information could be obtained by measuring the load's impedance with an impedance analyzer (or "impedance bridge"), the SWR meter is simpler and more robust for this purpose.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] By measuring the magnitude of the impedance mismatch at the transmitter output it reveals problems due to either the antenna or the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] SWR is used as a measure of impedance matching of a load to the characteristic impedance of a transmission line carrying radio frequency (RF) signals.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This especially applies to transmission lines connecting radio transmitters and receivers with their antennas, as well as similar uses of RF cables such as cable television connections to TV receivers and distribution amplifiers.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Impedance matching is achieved when the source impedance is the complex conjugate of the load impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The easiest way of achieving this, and the way that minimizes losses along the transmission line, is for the imaginary part of the complex impedance of both the source and load to be zero, that is, pure resistances, equal to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] When there is a mismatch between the load impedance and the transmission line, part of the forward wave sent toward the load is reflected back along the transmission line towards the source.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The source then sees a different impedance than it expects which can lead to lesser (or in some cases, more) power being supplied by it, the result being very sensitive to the electrical length of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Such a mismatch is usually undesired and results in standing waves along the transmission line which magnifies transmission line losses (significant at higher frequencies and for longer cables).
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The SWR is a measure of the depth of those standing waves and is, therefore, a measure of the matching of the load to the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] A matched load would result in an SWR of 1:1 implying no reflected wave.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] An infinite SWR represents complete reflection by a load unable to absorb electrical power, with all the incident power reflected back towards the source.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] It should be understood that the match of a load to the transmission line is different from the match of a *source* to the transmission line or the match of a source to the load *seen through* the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] However the SWR will generally not be 1:1, depending only on Zload and Z0.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] With a different length of transmission line, the source will see a different impedance than Zload which may or may not be a good match to the source.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Sometimes this is deliberate, as when a quarter-wave matching section is used to improve the match between an otherwise mismatched source and load.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] However typical RF sources such as transmitters and signal generators are designed to look into a purely resistive load impedance such as 50Ω or 75Ω, corresponding to common transmission lines' characteristic impedances.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In those cases, matching the load to the transmission line, Zload = Z0, *always* ensures that the source will see the same load impedance as if the transmission line weren't there.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This condition (Zload = Z0) also means that the load seen by the source is independent of the transmission line's electrical length.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] So in practice, a good SWR (near 1:1) implies a transmitter's output seeing the exact impedance it expects for optimum and safe operation.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The voltage component of a standing wave in a uniform transmission line consists of the forward wave (with complex amplitude $V_{f}$ ) superimposed on the reflected wave (with complex amplitude $V_{r}$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] A wave is partly reflected when a transmission line is terminated with an impedance unequal to its characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] $\Gamma$ is a complex number that describes both the magnitude and the phase shift of the reflection.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The SWR directly corresponds to the magnitude of $\Gamma$ .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Since the magnitude of $\Gamma$ always falls in the range [0,1], the SWR is always greater than or equal to unity.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Note that the *phase* of *V*f and *V*r vary along the transmission line in opposite directions to each other.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Therefore, the complex-valued reflection coefficient $\Gamma$ varies as well, but only in phase.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] With the SWR dependent *only* on the complex magnitude of $\Gamma$ , it can be seen that the SWR measured at *any* point along the transmission line (neglecting transmission line losses) obtains an identical reading.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] By sampling the complex voltage and current at the point of insertion, an SWR meter is able to compute the effective forward and reflected voltages on the transmission line for the characteristic impedance for which the SWR meter has been designed.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Since the forward and reflected power is related to the square of the forward and reflected voltages, some SWR meters also display the forward and reflected power.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] with the ratio or its reciprocal is chosen to obtain a value greater than unity.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Thus taking the real part of the complex quantity inside the parenthesis, the actual voltage consists of a sine wave at frequency f with a peak amplitude equal to the complex magnitude of V, and with a phase given by the phase of the complex V.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Since we are interested in the variations of the *magnitude* of Vnet along the line (as a function of x), we shall solve instead for the squared magnitude of that quantity, which simplifies the mathematics.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Along the line, the above expression for $\ |V_{\mathsf {net}}(x)|^{2}\$ is seen to oscillate sinusoidally between $\ |V_{\mathsf {min}}|^{2}\$ and $\ |V_{\mathsf {max}}|^{2}\$ with a period of ⁠ 2π /2k ⁠ .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This is *half* of the guided wavelength λ = ⁠ 2π / k ⁠ for the frequency f .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] That can be seen as due to interference between two waves of that frequency which are travelling in *opposite* directions.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] For example, at a frequency f = 20 MHz (free space wavelength of 15 m) in a transmission line whose velocity factor is 0.67 , the guided wavelength (distance between voltage peaks of the forward wave alone) would be λ = 10 m .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] At instances when the forward wave at x = 0 is at zero phase (peak voltage) then at x = 10 m it would also be at zero phase, but at x = 5 m it would be at 180° phase (peak *negative* voltage).
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] On the other hand, the magnitude of the voltage due to a standing wave produced by its addition to a reflected wave, would have a wavelength between peaks of only ⁠1/2⁠λ = 5 m .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Depending on the location of the load and phase of reflection, there might be a peak in the magnitude of Vnet at x = 1.3 m .
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Then there would be another peak found where |Vnet| = Vmax at x = 6.3 m , whereas it would find minima of the standing wave at x = 3.8 m, 8.8 m, etc.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The most common case for measuring and examining SWR is when installing and tuning transmitting antennas.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] When a transmitter is connected to an antenna by a feed line, the driving point impedance of the antenna must match the characteristic impedance of the feed line in order for the transmitter to see the impedance it was designed for (the impedance of the feed line, usually 50 or 75 ohms).
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The impedance of a particular antenna design can vary due to a number of factors that cannot always be clearly identified.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This includes the transmitter frequency (as compared to the antenna's design or resonant frequency), the antenna's height above and quality of the ground, proximity to large metal structures, and variations in the exact size of the conductors used to construct the antenna.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] When an antenna and feed line do not have matching impedances, the transmitter sees an unexpected impedance, where it might not be able to produce its full power, and can even damage the transmitter in some cases.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The reflected power in the transmission line increases the average current and therefore losses in the transmission line compared to power actually delivered to the load.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] It is the interaction of these reflected waves with forward waves which causes standing wave patterns, with the negative repercussions we have noted.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Matching the impedance of the antenna to the impedance of the feed line can sometimes be accomplished through adjusting the antenna itself, but otherwise is possible using an antenna tuner, an impedance matching device.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Installing a tuner in between the transmitter and the feed line can also transform the impedance seen at the transmitter end of the feed line to one preferred by the transmitter.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] However, in the latter case, the feed line still has a high SWR present, with the resulting increased feed line losses unmitigated.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The magnitude of those losses is dependent on the type of transmission line, and its length.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] For example, a certain antenna used well away from its resonant frequency may have an SWR of 6:1.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] For a frequency of 3.5 MHz, with that antenna fed through 75 meters of RG-8A coax, the loss due to standing waves would be 2.2 dB.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] However the same 6:1 mismatch through 75 meters of RG-8A coax would incur 10.8 dB of loss at 146 MHz.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Thus, a better match of the antenna to the feed line, that is, a lower SWR, becomes increasingly important with increasing frequency, even if the transmitter is able to accommodate the impedance seen (or an antenna tuner is used between the transmitter and feed line).
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Certain types of transmissions can suffer other negative effects from reflected waves on a transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Analog TV can experience "ghosts" from delayed signals bouncing back and forth on a long line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] FM stereo can also be affected and digital signals can experience delayed pulses leading to bit errors.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Whenever the delay times for a signal going back down and then again up the line are comparable to the modulation time constants, effects occur.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] For this reason, these types of transmissions require a low SWR on the feedline, even if SWR induced loss might be acceptable and matching is done at the transmitter.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Many different methods can be used to measure standing wave ratio.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The most intuitive method uses a slotted line which is a section of transmission line with an open slot which allows a probe to detect the actual voltage at various points along the line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Thus the maximum and minimum values can be compared directly.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This method is used at VHF and higher frequencies.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] At lower frequencies, such lines are impractically long.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Directional couplers can be used at HF through microwave frequencies.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Some are a quarter wave or more long, which restricts their use to the higher frequencies.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Other types of directional couplers sample the current and voltage at a single point in the transmission path and mathematically combine them in such a way as to represent the power flowing in one direction.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The common type of SWR / power meter used in amateur operation may contain a dual directional coupler.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Other types use a single coupler which can be rotated 180 degrees to sample power flowing in either direction.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Unidirectional couplers of this type are available for many frequency ranges and power levels and with appropriate coupling values for the analog meter used.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The forward and reflected power measured by directional couplers can be used to calculate SWR.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The computations can be done mathematically in analog or digital form or by using graphical methods built into the meter as an additional scale or by reading from the crossing point between two needles on the same meter.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The above measuring instruments can be used "in line" that is, the full power of the transmitter can pass through the measuring device so as to allow continuous monitoring of SWR.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Other instruments, such as network analyzers, low power directional couplers and antenna bridges use low power for the measurement and must be connected in place of the transmitter.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Bridge circuits can be used to directly measure the real and imaginary parts of a load impedance and to use those values to derive SWR.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] These methods can provide more information than just SWR or forward and reflected power.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Stand alone antenna analyzers use various measuring methods and can display SWR and other parameters plotted against frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] By using directional couplers and a bridge in combination, it is possible to make an in line instrument that reads directly in complex impedance or in SWR.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Stand alone antenna analyzers also are available that measure multiple parameters.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The term *power standing wave ratio* (PSWR) is sometimes referred to, and defined as, the square of the voltage standing wave ratio.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The term is widely cited as "misleading".
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] However it does correspond to one type of measurement of SWR using what was formerly a standard measuring instrument at microwave frequencies, the slotted line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The slotted line is a waveguide (or air-filled coaxial line) in which a small sensing antenna which is part of a *crystal detector* or *detector* is placed in the electric field in the line.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The voltage induced in the antenna is rectified by either a point contact diode (crystal rectifier) or a Schottky barrier diode that is incorporated in the detector.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] These detectors have a square law output for low levels of input.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Readings therefore corresponded to the square of the electric field along the slot, *E*2(*x*), with maximum and minimum readings of *E*2max and *E*2min found as the probe is moved along the slot.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The ratio of these yields the *square* of the SWR, the so-called PSWR.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] This technique of rationalization of terms is fraught with problems.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The square law behavior of the detector diode is exhibited only when the voltage across the diode is below the knee of the diode.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Once the detected voltage exceeds the knee, the response of the diode becomes nearly linear.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In this mode the diode and its associated filtering capacitor produce a voltage that is proportional to the peak of the sampled voltage.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] The operator of such a detector would not have a ready indication as to the mode in which the detector diode is operating and therefore differentiating the results between SWR or so called PSWR is not practical.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Perhaps even worse, is the common case where the minimum detected voltage is below the knee and the maximum voltage is above the knee.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In this case, the computed results are largely meaningless.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] Thus the terms PSWR and Power Standing Wave Ratio are deprecated and should be considered only from a legacy measurement perspective.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] SWR can also have a detrimental impact upon the performance of microwave-based medical applications.
[src:transmission-lines/standing-wave-ratio] In microwave electrosurgery an antenna that is placed directly into tissue may not always have an optimal match with the feedline resulting in standing waves, the presence of which can affect monitoring components used to measure power levels, making such measurements less reliable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In electrical engineering, a **transmission line** is a specialized cable or other structure designed to conduct electromagnetic waves in a contained manner.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The term applies when the conductors are long enough that the wave nature of the transmission must be taken into account.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] This applies especially to radio-frequency engineering because the short wavelengths mean that wave phenomena arise over very short distances (this can be as short as millimetres depending on frequency).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] However, the theory of transmission lines was historically developed to explain phenomena on very long telegraph lines, especially submarine telegraph cables.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] RF engineers commonly use short pieces of transmission line, usually in the form of printed planar transmission lines, arranged in certain patterns to build circuits such as filters.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These circuits, known as distributed-element circuits, are an alternative to traditional circuits using discrete capacitors and inductors.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Ordinary electrical cables suffice to carry low frequency alternating current (AC), such as mains power, which reverses direction 100 to 120 times per second, and audio signals.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] However, they are not generally used to carry currents in the radio frequency range, above about 30 kHz, because the energy tends to radiate off the cable as radio waves, causing power losses.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Radio frequency currents also tend to reflect from discontinuities in the cable such as connectors and joints, and travel back down the cable toward the source.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These reflections act as bottlenecks, preventing the signal power from reaching the destination.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Transmission lines use specialized construction, and impedance matching, to carry electromagnetic signals with minimal reflections and power losses.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The distinguishing feature of most transmission lines is that they have uniform cross sectional dimensions along their length, giving them a uniform impedance, called the *characteristic impedance*, to prevent reflections.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Types of transmission line include parallel line (ladder line, twisted pair), coaxial cable, and planar transmission lines such as stripline and microstrip.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The higher the frequency of electromagnetic waves moving through a given cable or medium, the shorter the wavelength of the waves.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Transmission lines become necessary when the transmitted frequency's wavelength is sufficiently short that the length of the cable becomes a significant part of a wavelength.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] At frequencies of microwave and higher, power losses in transmission lines become excessive, and waveguides are used instead, which function as "pipes" to confine and guide the electromagnetic waves.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Some sources define waveguides as a type of transmission line; however, this article will not include them.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Mathematical analysis of the behaviour of electrical transmission lines grew out of the work of James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Oliver Heaviside.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In 1855, Lord Kelvin formulated a diffusion model of the current in a submarine cable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The model correctly predicted the poor performance of the 1858 trans-Atlantic submarine telegraph cable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In 1885, Heaviside published the first papers that described his analysis of propagation in cables and the modern form of the telegrapher's equations.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In the simplest case, the network is assumed to be linear (i.e. the complex voltage across either port is proportional to the complex current flowing into it when there are no reflections), and the two ports are assumed to be interchangeable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Typical values of $Z_{0}$ are 50 or 75 ohms for a coaxial cable, about 100 ohms for a twisted pair of wires, and about 300 ohms for a common type of untwisted pair used in radio transmission.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Propagation delay is proportional to the length of the transmission line and is never less than the length divided by the speed of light.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Typical delays for modern communication transmission lines vary from 3.33 ns/m to 5 ns/m.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] When sending power down a transmission line, it is usually desirable that as much power as possible will be absorbed by the load and as little as possible will be reflected back to the source.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] This can be ensured by making the load impedance equal to $Z_{0}$ , in which case the transmission line is said to be *matched*.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Some of the power that is fed into a transmission line is lost because of its resistance.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] This effect is called *ohmic* or *resistive* loss (see ohmic heating).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] At high frequencies, another effect called *dielectric loss* becomes significant, adding to the losses caused by resistance.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Dielectric loss is caused when the insulating material inside the transmission line absorbs energy from the alternating electric field and converts it to heat (see dielectric heating).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The transmission line is modelled with a resistance ( R ) and inductance ( L ) in series with a capacitance ( C ) and conductance ( G ) in parallel.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The resistance and conductance contribute to the loss in a transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The total loss of power in a transmission line is often specified in decibels per metre (dB/m), and always depends on the frequency of the signal.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The manufacturer often supplies a chart showing the loss in dB/m at a range of frequencies.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A loss of 3 dB corresponds approximately to a halving of the power.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Propagation delay is often specified in units of nanoseconds per metre.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] While propagation delay usually depends on the frequency of the signal, transmission lines are typically operated over frequency ranges where the propagation delay is approximately constant.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The **telegrapher's equations** (or just **telegraph equations**) are a pair of linear differential equations which describe the voltage ( V ) and current ( I ) on an electrical transmission line with distance and time.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] They were developed by Oliver Heaviside who created the *transmission line model*, and are based on Maxwell's equations.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The transmission line model is an example of the distributed-element model.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The model consists of an *infinite series* of the elements shown in the figure, and the values of the components are specified *per unit length* so the picture of the component can be misleading.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] R , L , C , and G may also be functions of frequency.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] An alternative notation is to use $R'$ , $L'$ , $C'$ and $G'$ to emphasize that the values are derivatives with respect to length.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These quantities can also be known as the primary line constants to distinguish from the secondary line constants derived from them, these being the propagation constant, attenuation constant and phase constant.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] When the elements R and G are negligibly small the transmission line is considered as a lossless structure.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In this hypothetical case, the model depends only on the L and C elements which greatly simplifies the analysis.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These are wave equations which have plane waves with equal propagation speed in the forward and reverse directions as solutions.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that electromagnetic waves propagate down transmission lines and in general, there is a reflected component that interferes with the original signal.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These equations are fundamental to transmission line theory.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the (complex) propagation constant.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] They are also wave equations, and have solutions similar to the special case, but which are a mixture of sines and cosines with exponential decay factors.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The constants $V_{(\pm )}$ must be determined from boundary conditions.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] where atan2 is the everywhere-defined form of two-parameter arctangent function, with arbitrary value zero when both arguments are zero.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] with the plus or minus signs chosen opposite to the direction of the wave's motion through the conducting medium.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] If R, G, L, and C are constants that are *not* frequency dependent and the Heaviside condition is met, then waves travel down the transmission line without phase distortion.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ of a transmission line is the ratio of the amplitude of a *single* voltage wave to its current wave.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Since most transmission lines also have a reflected wave, the characteristic impedance is generally not the impedance that is measured on the line.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant and ${\mathit {\Gamma }}_{\mathrm {L} }={\frac {\,Z_{\mathrm {L} }-Z_{0}\,}{Z_{\mathrm {L} }+Z_{0}}}$ is the voltage reflection coefficient measured at the load end of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In calculating $\beta ,$ the wavelength is generally different *inside* the transmission line to what it would be in free-space.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Consequently, the velocity factor of the material the transmission line is made of needs to be taken into account when doing such a calculation.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] for all $n\,.$ This includes the case when $n=0$ , meaning that the length of the transmission line is negligibly small compared to the wavelength.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that the transmission line can be ignored (i.e. treated as a wire) in either case.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Transmission lines are mainly defined in using ABCD parameters or transmission parameters.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] As $A=D$ , the transmission lines are symmetric networks.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] It also satisfies reciprocity condition $AD-BC=1$ .
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, Y12 = Y21, and Y11 = Y22.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Impedance (Z) parameters are defined by applying a fixed current into one port (I1) of a transmission line with the other port open and measuring the resulting voltage on each port (V1, V2) and computing the impedance parameter Z11 is V1/I1, and the impedance parameter Z12 is V2/I1.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, V12 = V21, and V11 = V22.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Unlike ideal lumped 2 port elements (resistors, capacitors, inductors, etc.) which do not have defined Z parameters, transmission lines have an internal path to ground, which permits the definition of Z parameters.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Scattering (S) matrix parameters model the electrical behavior of the transmission line with matched loads at each termination.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] For lossless and lossy transmission lines respectively, the S parameter matrix is as follows, using standard hyperbolic to circular complex translations.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Transmission lines may be placed in proximity to each other such that they electrically interact, such as two microstrip lines in close proximity.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Such transmission lines are said to be coupled transmission lines.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Coupled transmission lines are characterized by an even and odd mode analysis.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The even mode is characterized by excitation of the two conductors with a signal of equal amplitude and phase.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The odd mode is characterized by excitation with signals of equal and opposite magnitude.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The even and odd modes each have their own characteristic impedances ( $Z_{0e}$ , $Z_{0o}$ ) and phase constants ( $\beta _{e}{\text{, }}\beta _{o}$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Lossy coupled transmission lines have their own even and odd mode attenuation constants ( $\alpha _{e}{\text{, }}\alpha _{o}$ ), which in turn leads to even and odd mode propagation constants ( $\gamma _{e}{\text{, }}\gamma _{o}$ ).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Coaxial lines confine virtually all of the electromagnetic wave to the area inside the cable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Coaxial lines can therefore be bent and twisted (subject to limits) without negative effects, and they can be strapped to conductive supports without inducing unwanted currents in them.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] However, at frequencies for which the wavelength (in the dielectric) is significantly shorter than the circumference of the cable other transverse modes can propagate.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These modes are classified into two groups, transverse electric (TE) and transverse magnetic (TM) waveguide modes.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] When more than one mode can exist, bends and other irregularities in the cable geometry can cause power to be transferred from one mode to another.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The most common use for coaxial cables is for television and other signals with bandwidth of multiple megahertz.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In the middle 20th century they carried long distance telephone connections.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Planar transmission lines are transmission lines with conductors, or in some cases dielectric strips, that are flat, ribbon-shaped lines.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] They are used to interconnect components on printed circuits and integrated circuits working at microwave frequencies because the planar type fits in well with the manufacturing methods for these components.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Several forms of planar transmission lines exist.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A microstrip circuit uses a thin flat conductor which is parallel to a ground plane.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Microstrip can be made by having a strip of copper on one side of a printed circuit board (PCB) or ceramic substrate while the other side is a continuous ground plane.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the insulating layer (PCB or ceramic) and the dielectric constant of the insulating layer determine the characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Microstrip is an open structure whereas coaxial cable is a closed structure.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A stripline circuit uses a flat strip of metal which is sandwiched between two parallel ground planes.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The insulating material of the substrate forms a dielectric.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the substrate and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the strip which is a transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A coplanar waveguide consists of a center strip and two adjacent outer conductors, all three of them flat structures that are deposited onto the same insulating substrate and thus are located in the same plane ("coplanar").
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The width of the center conductor, the distance between inner and outer conductors, and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the coplanar transmission line.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A balanced line is a transmission line consisting of two conductors of the same type, and equal impedance to ground and other circuits.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] There are many formats of balanced lines, amongst the most common are twisted pair, star quad and twin-lead.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Twisted pairs are commonly used for terrestrial telephone communications.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In such cables, many pairs are grouped together in a single cable, from two to several thousand.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The format is also used for data network distribution inside buildings, but the cable is more expensive because the transmission line parameters are tightly controlled.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Star quad is a four-conductor cable in which all four conductors are twisted together around the cable axis.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] It is sometimes used for two circuits, such as 4-wire telephony and other telecommunications applications.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In this configuration each pair uses two non-adjacent conductors.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Other times it is used for a single, balanced line, such as audio applications and 2-wire telephony.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] In this configuration two non-adjacent conductors are terminated together at both ends of the cable, and the other two conductors are also terminated together.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] When used for two circuits, crosstalk is reduced relative to cables with two separate twisted pairs.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] When used for a single, balanced line, magnetic interference picked up by the cable arrives as a virtually perfect common mode signal, which is easily removed by coupling transformers.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The combined benefits of twisting, balanced signalling, and quadrupole pattern give outstanding noise immunity, especially advantageous for low signal level applications such as microphone cables, even when installed very close to a power cable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The disadvantage is that star quad, in combining two conductors, typically has double the capacitance of similar two-conductor twisted and shielded audio cable.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] High capacitance causes increasing distortion and greater loss of high frequencies as distance increases.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Twin-lead consists of a pair of conductors held apart by a continuous insulator.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] By holding the conductors a known distance apart, the geometry is fixed and the line characteristics are reliably consistent.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] It is lower loss than coaxial cable because the characteristic impedance of twin-lead is generally higher than coaxial cable, leading to lower resistive losses due to the reduced current.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] However, it is more susceptible to interference.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Lecher lines are a form of parallel conductor that can be used at UHF for creating resonant circuits.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] They are a convenient practical format that fills the gap between lumped components (used at HF/VHF) and resonant cavities (used at UHF/SHF).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Unbalanced lines were formerly much used for telegraph transmission, but this form of communication has now fallen into disuse.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Cables are similar to twisted pair in that many cores are bundled into the same cable but only one conductor is provided per circuit and there is no twisting.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] All the circuits on the same route use a common path for the return current (earth return).
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] There is a power transmission version of single-wire earth return in use in many locations.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Electrical transmission lines are very widely used to transmit high frequency signals over long or short distances with minimum power loss.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] One familiar example is the down lead from a TV or radio aerial to the receiver.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A large variety of circuits can also be constructed with transmission lines including impedance matching circuits, filters, power dividers and directional couplers.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A stepped transmission line is used for broad range impedance matching.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] It can be considered as multiple transmission line segments connected in series, with the characteristic impedance of each individual element to be $Z_{\mathrm {0,i} }$ .
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] where $\beta _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the wave number of the $\mathrm {i}$ -th transmission line segment and $\ell _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the length of this segment, and $Z_{\mathrm {i} }$ is the front-end impedance that loads the $\mathrm {i}$ -th segment.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] At higher frequencies, the reactive parasitic effects of real world lumped elements, including inductors and capacitors, limits their usefulness.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Therefore, it is sometimes useful to approximate the electrical characteristics of inductors and capacitors with transmission lines at the higher frequencies using Richards' transformations and then substitute the transmission lines for the lumped elements.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] More accurate forms of multimode high frequency inductor modeling with transmission lines exist for advanced designers.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] If a short-circuited or open-circuited transmission line is wired in parallel with a line used to transfer signals from point A to point B, then it will function as a filter.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The method for making stubs is similar to the method for using Lecher lines for crude frequency measurement, but it is 'working backwards'.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] One method recommended in the RSGB's radiocommunication handbook is to take an open-circuited length of transmission line wired in parallel with the feeder delivering signals from an aerial.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] By cutting the free end of the transmission line, a minimum in the strength of the signal observed at a receiver can be found.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] At this stage the stub filter will reject this frequency and the odd harmonics, but if the free end of the stub is shorted then the stub will become a filter rejecting the even harmonics.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Wideband filters can be achieved using multiple stubs.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] However, this is a somewhat dated technique.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Much more compact filters can be made with other methods such as parallel-line resonators.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] Transmission lines are used as pulse generators.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] By charging the transmission line and then discharging it into a resistive load, a rectangular pulse equal in length to twice the electrical length of the line can be obtained, although with half the voltage.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] A Blumlein transmission line is a related pulse forming device that overcomes this limitation.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] These are sometimes used as the pulsed power sources for radar transmitters and other devices.
[src:transmission-lines/transmission-line] The theory of sound wave propagation is very similar mathematically to that of electromagnetic waves, so techniques from transmission line theory are also used to build structures to conduct acoustic waves; and these are called acoustic transmission lines.
